## 🚫 What NOT to Do

### **NEVER:**
1. ❌ Push directly to `master` (or `develop` when in a worktree)
2. ❌ Create PRs targeting `master` (unless production release)
3. ❌ Commit without descriptive messages
4. ❌ Create PRs without proper descriptions
5. ❌ Merge your own PRs without approval
6. ❌ Force push (`git push -f`) to shared branches
7. ❌ Commit sensitive data (credentials, tokens, etc.)
8. ❌ Skip testing before creating PR
9. ❌ Ignore SwiftLint warnings
10. ❌ Leave commented-out code
11. ❌ Create massive PRs (>500 lines changed)
12. ❌ **Run `git checkout develop` or `git checkout master` from inside a worktree**
13. ❌ **Create, edit, or write files while on `develop` inside a worktree**
14. ❌ **Switch branches inside a worktree for ANY reason** — worktrees are branch-locked

### **ALWAYS:**
1. ✅ Create feature branches from `develop` (when in worktrees or for larger changes)
2. ✅ Target `develop` for all PRs (NOT `master`)
3. ✅ For direct commits to `develop`: verify you're NOT in a worktree first
4. ✅ **Run the Pre-Work Verification check at the START of every task** (see Worktree Rules above)
5. ✅ **Confirm your current branch is your worktree branch before ANY file operations**
6. ✅ Write clear commit messages
7. ✅ Include PR descriptions with context
8. ✅ Wait for review before merging (for PRs)
9. ✅ Test your changes locally
10. ✅ Keep PRs focused and reasonably sized
11. ✅ Update documentation when needed
12. ✅ Follow existing code patterns
13. ✅ Run SwiftLint before committing
14. ✅ Use the TodoWrite tool to track progress

